11. Why can't two containers use the same Host Port?

Example:

docker run -p 8080:80 nginx

Another container:

docker run -p 8080:80 nginx

❌ Docker gives an error because Host Port 8080 is already in use.

Correct:

docker run -p 8080:80 nginx
docker run -p 8081:80 nginx

Both containers still use Port 80 internally.

12. Dockerfile with Nginx

Example:

FROM ubuntu

RUN apt update

RUN apt install -y nginx

EXPOSE 80

CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]
13. Why do we use daemon off;?

Normally Nginx starts in the background (daemon mode).

Docker containers stay alive only while the main process is running.

Using:

CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]

keeps Nginx running in the foreground so the container stays alive.

14. Common Commands

Build Image

docker build -t my-nginx:v1 .

Run Container

docker run -d --name my-nginx -p 8080:80 my-nginx:v1

List Networks

docker network ls

Inspect Bridge Network

docker network inspect bridge

List Running Containers

docker ps

List All Containers

docker ps -a

View Logs

docker logs <container-id>
⭐ Interview Questions
Q1. Why is Port Mapping required?

Because the container has its own isolated network. Port mapping connects a host port to the container port so that applications inside the container can be accessed from outside.

Q2. What is the difference between EXPOSE and -p?
EXPOSE documents the application's listening port inside the container.
-p publishes the container port to the host, making it accessible externally.
Q3. What are the default Docker networks?
Bridge
Host
None
Q4. Why can't two containers use the same Host Port?

Because a host port can be bound to only one application at a time. Docker will return a "port already allocated" error.

Q5. Does every Docker container get its own IP Address?

Yes. Docker automatically assigns each container a unique IP address from the network's subnet.
